<p class="story-body-text" style="background: white; margin: 0in 0in 12.0pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">Iâm delighted to invite university students to apply for my 2018 win-a-trip contest. Iâve been holding these contests since 2006, and taking the winner along with me on a reporting trip to cover global poverty and social justice issues. My aim is to generate interest in neglected global issues and get more people writing about them.</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" style="background: white; margin: 0in 0in 12.0pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">The winner will write pieces for me on the New York Times website. HBO did a documentary called âReporterâ based on my 2007 win-a-trip journey to Congo; itâs on Amazon and iTunes if you want to see what youâre getting yourself in for. The contest begins immediately and you must apply by Sunday, Dec. 10<sup>th</sup>, 2017.</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-15894"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" style="background: white; margin: 0in 0in 12.0pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">Read theÂ </span><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;"><a href="https://kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2017/11/17/win-a-trip-with-nick-kristof-2018-contest-rules/?module=BlogPost-Title&amp;version=Blog%20Main&amp;action=Click&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Body">full rules here</a></span><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">. The contest is open to students enrolled in an American college or university, either as an undergraduate or graduate. <strong>To apply, submit an essay explaining why I should pick you.</strong> Please donât gush about my reporting â just explain what you bring to the table. It might be that youâre a great writer or photographer, or it might be that you grew up poor and know something about poverty, or grew up rich and donât know a thing about it. Iâm not looking for expertise but for intelligence and great communication skills so that your posts, photos and social media will make other students interested in these issues and generate some conversations. If you blog or have other writing, photography or video experience, mention it and send links.</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" style="background: white; margin: 0in 0in 12.0pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">To enter,Â </span><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;"><a href="https://www.cgdev.org/webform/nick-kristof-win-trip-2018">use this form</a></span><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">Â at the Center for Global Development website. The center will help me winnow down the applicants to a much smaller pool of finalists, and then with the help of my assistant, Zoe Greenberg, Iâll choose the winner. My aim is to travel for a week or two, perhaps in the late spring or early summer. Iâll try to work around the winnerâs schedule, but if you know for sure you wonât be able to take the time off, then please donât apply. Your expenses will be covered, but thereâs no cash award, and you may have to pay taxes on the value of the trip. Iâm not sure just where weâll travel, but Central African Republic is one possibility, and Bangladesh is another. If you speak French, mention that, but itâs certainly not a requirement.</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" style="background: white; margin: 0in 0in 12.0pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">Also, remember that the traveling is sometimes tough. The joke within The New York Times is that first prize is a trip with me; second prize is two trips with me. We will be bouncing over awful roads, weâll be eating wretched food, and you may get sick. âHotelâ rooms may come with bedbugs and rats. And weâll be on the go from dawn to dusk. To get a sense of what the past winners have done, check out </span><a href="https://kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2017/07/11/the-top-5-reporting-lessons-i-learned-in-liberia/"><span style="font-family: Georgia;">Aneri Pattaniâs post from Liberia</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;"> in 2017, Â </span><a href="//kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/10/15/breast-milk-an-education-and-a-giant-baby/"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;">Austin Meyerâs post on malnutrition</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">Â in India,Â <a href="//kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/17/win-a-trip-2011-saumya-reports-from-morocco/"><span style="color: #326891;">Saumya Daveâs first impressions of Morocco</span></a>Â in 2011,Â </span><a href="//kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/05/13/win-a-trip-reminders-of-the-south/"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;">Paul Bowerâs reflections in 2009</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">Â on how religion in Liberia shares many similarities with the South, orÂ </span><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2006/09/26/opinion/26kristof.html"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;">my 2006 visit to the Dzanga-Sangha area</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">Â in the Central African Republic to see gorillas and elephants with Casey Parks. You can also see what past win-a-trip winners are up to; the 2013 winner,Â </span><a href="//kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/author/erin-luhmann/"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;">Erin Luhmann</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">, caught up withÂ </span><a href="//kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/06/28/where-win-a-trip-winners-are-now/"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;">the previous winners</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">, going back to the Casey in 2006. In 2016, I did something different: winner Cassidy McDonald and IÂ </span><a href="//kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/author/cassidy-mcdonald/"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;">reported on domestic poverty</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">Â here in the United States.</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" style="background: white; margin: 0in 0in 12.0pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">If you want to get a sense of the issues I cover and care about, subscribe to myÂ </span><a href="//www.nytimes.com/kristofemail"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;">free email newsletter</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">. But donât feel you need to agree with me to apply or win! <strong>And Iâd like to see a diverse pool of applicants, so if you donât look like me, thatâs welcome.Â Writers of color, women, LGBTQ+ students, conservatives, liberals, artists, athletes, veterans â send in your essays!</strong></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" style="background: white; margin: 0in 0in 12.0pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">One other suggestion. Only one person will win this trip, but you can always try to make your own trip. Africa can be relatively expensive, but traveling around Nicaragua or India/Bangladesh, or Vietnam/Cambodia may be more affordable. You may also be able to get a job teaching English to defray expenses. And for that matter, there are many opportunities to leave your comfort zone without leaving this country â tutor in a prison, or in an inner city school. Over the years, Iâve heard from a number of win-a-trip applicants who, disgusted by my poor judgment in failing to pick them, went off on their own journeys and had life-shaping experiences. So if you donât win my trip, win your own! You may also find ideas for places to volunteer abroad atÂ </span><a href="//omprakash.org/"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;">omprakash.org</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">Â orÂ </span><a href="//idealist.org/"><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #326891;">idealist.org</span></a><span style="font-family: Georgia; color: #333333;">.</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
